<h1>Attorney General Ellison sues Trump Administration for rule curtailing environmental review of federal actions</h1>
	<p class="lede">Rule would limit Minnesotansâ participation, hurt vulnerable communitiesâ pursuit of environmental justice</p>

	<p><strong>August 29, 2020 (SAINT PAUL)</strong>Â â Minnesota Attorney General Keith Ellison announced today that he has joined a coalition of 22 states, territories, and local governmentsÂ in filing aÂ <a href="https://oag.ca.gov/system/files/attachments/press-docs/%5B1%5D%20Complaint%20for%20Declaratory%20and%20Injunctive%20Relief.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" data-auth="NotApplicable">lawsuit</a>Â that challenges the Trump Administration&rsquo;s unlawful final rule curtailingÂ environmental review of federal actionsÂ under theÂ National Environmental Policy Act (NEPA). Until now, NEPA has required that federal agencies review and assess the impact of their actions on the environment. The final rule also limits public participation in the review process, thereby robbingÂ vulnerable communities of the opportunity to make their voices heard on actions that are likely to have adverse impacts on their environment and health and their pursuit of environmental justice.Â </p>	
	<p>In the lawsuit, the coalition argues that the final rule abandons informed decision making, public participation, and environmental and public health protections in violation of the Administrative Procedure Act (APA) andÂ NEPA.Â </p>
	<p>&ldquo;My job is to protect Minnesotans, especially the most vulnerable, when the federal government won&rsquo;t,&rdquo; Attorney General Ellison said. &ldquo;Once again, the Trump Administration is deliberately making it harder for Minnesotans to live with dignity and respect, and to make their voices heard on environmental decisions that concern their health and wellbeing. Once again, they&rsquo;re taking aim at vulnerable communities who have suffered the most from environmental injustice. And we allege that once again, they&rsquo;ve broken the law in doing so. I&rsquo;ve joined a broad coalition to hold them accountable in court.&rdquo;Â </p>
	<p>Enacted in 1969,Â NEPAÂ is one of the nation&rsquo;s foremost environmental statutes.Â NEPAÂ requires that before any federal agency undertakesÂ &ldquo;majorÂ Federal actionsÂ significantly affecting the quality of the human environment,&rdquo; it must consider the environmental impacts of the proposed actions, alternatives to the actions, and any available mitigation measures. Numerous federal actions, from the approval of significant energy and infrastructure projects to key decisions concerning the management of federal public lands, require compliance withÂ NEPA.Â Â </p>
	<p>Millions of Minnesotans, as well as Minnesota state agencies, have participated in NEPA review processes for major infrastructure projects in Minnesota, such as PolyMet&rsquo;s NorthMet mine and Enbridge Energy&rsquo;s Line 3 replacement project. Public participation in projects that require federal permits is critical to ensure that Minnesotans have a voice in federal decisions.Â </p>
	<p>On July 15, 2020, the Trump Administration&rsquo;s Council on Environmental Quality announced a final rule upending the requirement thatÂ federal agenciesÂ comprehensively evaluate the impacts of their actions on the environment and public health.Â This will result in agencies taking actions without fully understanding the impacts of those actions on climate change, overburdened and underserved communities, water and air quality, and sensitive, threatened, and endangered wildlife. In addition, the final rule so severely limitsÂ NEPA&rsquo;s public participation process that it threatens to render it a meaningless paperwork exercise.Â </p>
	<p>In the lawsuit, the coalition argues that the final rule violatesÂ NEPAÂ and APA because it:Â </p>
	<ul>
	  <li>is contrary toÂ NEPA&rsquo;s language and purpose and exceeds the Council on Environmental Quality&rsquo;s statutory authority;Â </li>
	  <li>is arbitrary, capricious, an abuse of discretion, and otherwise not in accordance with law;Â andÂ </li>
	  <li>wasÂ promulgated without preparing an Environmental Assessment or an Environmental Impact Statement evaluating the rule&rsquo;s environmental and public health impacts.Â </li>
    </ul>
	<p>AttorneyÂ General Ellison joinsÂ the California Attorney General Xavier Becerra and Washington Attorney General Bob Ferguson, who led the coalition, and the attorneys general of Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Maine, Maryland,Â Massachusetts,Â Nevada, New Jersey, New Mexico,Â New York, North Carolina, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont, the District of Columbia, and Guam,Â as well as the Connecticut Department of Environmental Protection, the City of New York, and Harris County, TexasÂ in filing the lawsuit.Â </p>
